EVEN ANALYSIS FOR PICO'S PRODUCTS\":\"Pico makes two products, P1 and P2, with budgeted details including selling price, cost per unit, and profit per unit. The case involves calculating the number of units needed to achieve a target profit, break-even revenue, and the impact of changes in material costs and fixed costs on break-even revenue.\"", "\"BREAK-EVEN ANALYSIS\":\"Break-even analysis involves calculating the selling price or volume needed to cover all costs and achieve zero profit or loss. It is a method used to determine the level of sales volume at which total revenues equal total costs, resulting in neither profit nor loss.\"", "\"MULTI-PRODUCT BREAK-EVEN ANALYSIS AND PROFIT CALCULATION\":\"Nerville makes and sells a range of three gardening products, E375, F294, and G142, with budgeted data including selling price, variable cost, contribution per unit, fixed cost, and profit per unit. The case involves calculating the break-even point and profit for multiple products.\"", "\"BREAKEVEN POINT OF PROJECT 1\":\"The breakeven point in sales value for Project 1 is calculated by dividing the fixed costs by the contribution-to-sales (C/S) ratio. The sales value of two room nights is $135, and the sales value of a pair of theatre tickets is $100, making a total of $235. The variable costs are $120 for two room nights and $95 for a pair of theatre tickets, resulting in a contribution of $20. The C/S ratio is 8.51% (20/235), and the breakeven point in revenue is $235,000 ($20,000/0.0851).\"", "\"FINANCIAL EFFECT OF PROJECT 2\":\"Project 2 will increase the fixed costs of the hotel from $600,000 to $800,000 per year. The revenue per occupied room will rise from $180 to $250, reflecting extra guest expenditure in the restaurant. The total cost at 8,000 occupied rooms is $1,560,000, with variable costs of $760,000 ($1,560,000 - $800,000 fixed costs), resulting in a variable cost per occupied room of $95. The breakeven point increases from 5,000 to 5,161 occupied rooms, but the budgeted occupancy is 7,300 occupied room nights, giving a margin of safety of 2,139 occupied room nights or 29%. The budgeted profit at 7,300 occupied room nights is $331,500.\"", "\"FINANCIAL VIABILITY ANALYSIS OF REPLACING CAF\u00c9 WITH CR\u00c8CHE AT HEALTH NUTS FITNESS CENTRE\":\"Health Nuts Fitness Centre is considering replacing its onsite caf\u00e9 with a cr\u00e8che. The fitness centre offers 'pay-as-you-go' gym facilities, with a capacity of 200 users and 100 car parking spaces. Customers pay $8.40 for gym access and unlimited time in the caf\u00e9, with an additional $1 for car park use. The average number of customers per day is 330, with 40 attending between 9.00am and 5.00pm. The total costs for June, excluding the caf\u00e9, are $48,000 in fixed costs and $1.20 in variable costs per customer. Half of the customers use the caf\u00e9, with an average spend of $2.20 per customer, 60% of which is on drinks with a 60% profit margin, and the remainder on food with a 40% profit margin.\"", "\"BUDGETED PROFIT OR LOSS FOR Q1\":", "\"NUMBER OF DAYS IN THE MONTH\":\"The total number of days in a month, which is 30.\"", "\"TOTAL CUSTOMERS FOR THE MONTH\":\"The total number of customers visiting the gym in a month, calculated as 13,500.\"", "\"ENTRY FEE\":\"The fee charged for entry to the gym, which is $8.40.\"", "\"CAR PARK FEE\":\"The fee charged for parking at the gym, which is $0.80.\"", "\"TOTAL SALES FROM GYM ENTRY/CAR PARK\":\"The total revenue generated from gym entry and car park fees, which is $124,200.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}